{
  "description": "Discontent with colonial rule began shortly after the defeat of France in the French and Indian War in 1763. Even though the colonies had fought in and supported the war, British Parliament imposed new taxes to compensate for wartime costs and turned control of the colonies' western lands over to the British officials in Montreal.",
  "date": "1763",
  "type": "triggering"
}

{
  "description": "Parliament passed the Stamp Act in March 1765, which imposed direct taxes on the colonies for the first time, requiring all official documents, newspapers, almanacs, and pamphlets to have stamps, sparking widespread colonial objection to taxation without representation.",
  "date": "1765-03",
  "type": "intermediate"
}

{
  "description": "In 1767, the British Parliament passed the Townshend Acts, which placed duties on several staple goods, including paper, glass, and tea, and established a Board of Customs in Boston to more rigorously execute trade regulations, intending to assert its authority over the colonies.",
  "date": "1767",
  "type": "intermediate"
}

{
  "description": "On March 5, 1770, a large crowd gathered around a group of British soldiers on a Boston street, grew threatening, and threw snowballs, rocks, and debris, causing the soldiers to panic and fire into the crowd, hitting 11 people and killing five civilians, which quickly turned colonial sentiment against the British.",
  "date": "1770-03-05",
  "type": "intermediate"
}

{
  "description": "On December 16, 1773, in a seminal event in the American Revolution's escalation, Sons of Liberty activists wearing costumes of Native Americans instigated the Boston Tea Party, during which they boarded and dumped chests of tea owned by the British East India Company into Boston Harbor.",
  "date": "1773-12-16",
  "type": "intermediate"
}

{
  "description": "The British government responded to the Boston Tea Party by passing four laws, known as the Intolerable Acts, which closed the port of Boston, altered the Massachusetts charter, allowed trials of British soldiers in Britain, and permitted housing of troops in homes, further darkening colonial opinion towards England.",
  "date": "1774",
  "type": "intermediate"
}

{
  "description": "In late 1774, 12 of the Thirteen Colonies sent delegates to the First Continental Congress in Philadelphia, which began coordinating Patriot resistance through underground networks of committees and called for a boycott of all British goods.",
  "date": "1774-09",
  "type": "intermediate"
}

{
  "description": "The American Revolutionary War was launched on April 19, 1775, in the Battles of Lexington and Concord, leading to Washington and the Continental Army responding by surrounding Boston, forcing the British to withdraw by sea in March 1776, and leaving Patriots in control in every colony.",
  "date": "1775-04-19",
  "type": "triggering"
}

{
  "description": "On July 4, 1776, the Second Continental Congress unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence, authored primarily by Thomas Jefferson, which embodied political philosophies of liberalism and republicanism, rejected monarchy and aristocracy, and proclaimed that 'all men are created equal', formalizing the cause of full independence.",
  "date": "1776-07-04",
  "type": "intermediate"
}

{
  "description": "On September 28, 1781, Washington, with support from Marquis de Lafayette, the French Army, and French Navy, led the Continental Army's most decisive victory, capturing roughly 7,500 British troops led by British general Charles Cornwallis during the Siege of Yorktown.",
  "date": "1781-09-28",
  "type": "intermediate"
}

{
  "description": "On September 3, 1783, the British signed the Treaty of Paris, granting their former colonies nearly all the territory east of the Mississippi River and south of the Great Lakes, codifying their independence and leading to the establishment of the sovereign United States of America.",
  "date": "1783-09-03",
  "type": "outcome"
}

{
  "description": "British Parliament's imposition of new taxes on the colonies after the French and Indian War directly caused widespread colonial rebellion and discontent because colonists viewed these taxes as a violation of their fundamental rights as Englishmen, specifically the right to be taxed only by their own elected representatives.",
  "status": "hypothetical"
}

{
  "description": "The British government's post-1763 policies, including new taxes, control over western lands, and the deployment of a standing army, eroded the colonists' long-held practice of self-governance fostered by salutary neglect, thereby escalating their demands from autonomy to full independence and armed resistance.",
  "status": "hypothetical"
}

{
  "description": "London's response to colonial protests, particularly the enactment of punitive laws like the Intolerable Acts after the Boston Tea Party, inadvertently expanded and intensified the revolutionary cause by effectively ending self-government in Massachusetts and demonstrating a clear British intent to suppress colonial liberties.",
  "status": "hypothetical"
}

{
  "description": "The fundamental conflict between the British Parliament's assertion of supreme lawmaking authority over the Empire and the American colonists' evolving understanding of their rights as Englishmen and their embrace of republicanism directly led to escalating tensions and ultimately armed revolution.",
  "status": "hypothetical"
}

